# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: william-branch-giles
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] Robertson was born in Martinsburg, West Virginia, the son of Franklin Pierce Robertson and Josephine Ragland (née Willis), just two weeks before fellow Virginia Senator Harry F.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] He graduated from the University of Richmond in 1907.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] Robertson established a private law practice following graduation, and soon embarked on a political career.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] He was elected to the Virginia State Senate as a Democrat in 1915 to represent Bedford and Rockbridge counties and Buena Vista, Virginia, in Senate district 22, replacing W.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] Robertson served from 1916 to 1922, when he resigned and was replaced by Samuel S.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] Lambeth Jr. in the February 1923 special session.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] The constituency was renumbered as the 23rd district in advance of the General Assembly's 1924 session.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] During World War I, Robertson enlisted and served in the United States Army, but was assigned stateside so he could continue that part-time elective office.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] Robertson served as Commonwealth Attorney for Rockbridge County, Virginia (an elective office per the Virginia constitution, which prohibited such officials from also serving as legislators or judges during their terms) from 1922 to 1928.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] In 1932, Robertson was elected from Virginia's 7th congressional district to the U.S.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] House of Representatives, and was reelected six times.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] In 1946, he won a special election for the right to complete the final two years of Senator Carter Glass's term and took office on the day after the election.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] He won the seat in his own right in 1948 and was reelected two more times without serious opposition.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] Among his legislation is the Pittman–Robertson Federal Aid in Wildlife Restoration Act which creates the formula for federal sharing of ammunition tax revenues with states to establish wildlife areas.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] The program is still in effect and remains a primary financing source for wildlife areas.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] Robertson was a typical member of the Byrd Organization, though his opinions differed at times and eventually became independent from the machine.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] Senate Committee on Banking, Housing, and Urban Affairs from 1959 to 1966.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] In 1956, Robertson was one of the 19 senators who signed the Southern Manifesto against the U.S.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] Board of Education of Topeka* (1954), which mandated schools' desegregation.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] Johnson sent his wife, Lady Bird Johnson, on a train trip through the South to encourage support for the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and the Voting Rights Act of 1965, Robertson was one of four Southern Senators who refused to meet with her on the whistle-stop trip.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] In retaliation, President Johnson personally recruited Virginia State Senator William B.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] Spong Jr., a considerably more liberal Democrat, to run against Robertson in the 1966 Democratic primary.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] Even some Byrd Democrats had moved away from resistance to integration as espoused by Robertson and the Organization's patriarch, Harry F.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] Meanwhile, the Twenty-Fourth Amendment and Voting Rights Act had combined to add black and lower-income voters.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] Spong defeated Robertson in the primary in one of the biggest upsets in Virginia political history.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] The Byrd Organization's long dominance of Virginia state politics had begun to end.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] In 1971, Robertson died in Lexington, Virginia and is buried in Stonewall Jackson Memorial Cemetery, later renamed Oak Grove Cemetery.
[src:william-branch-giles/a-willis-robertson] His papers are held at the Swem Library at the College of William and Mary.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was born in New Jersey and moved frequently during her childhood before her family settled in Virginia.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] She earned degrees from the University of Virginia and Purdue University.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] From 2006 to 2014, she was an officer in the Central Intelligence Agency.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] House of Representatives in 2018, unseating incumbent Republican Dave Brat.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] She was reelected in 2020 and 2022 before leaving Congress to run for governor.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was elected governor of Virginia in 2025, defeating the Republican nominee, Lieutenant Governor Winsome Earle-Sears.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] She is Virginia's first female governor.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] As governor, Spanberger signed a controversial "assault weapons" ban, increased the state's minimum wage, vetoed recreational cannabis retail market and collective bargaining legislation, and supported the 2026 Virginia redistricting referendum.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was born Abigail Anne Davis in Red Bank, New Jersey, on August 7, 1979, her father, Martin Davis, a police officer, and her mother, Eileen Davis, a nurse.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] She knew from a young age that she wanted to be a spy, writing her diary in code.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Her family moved often when she was young, living in Maine, the New York City area, and Philadelphia, before settling in Short Pump, Virginia, when she was 13.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Her father had moved from policing to federal law enforcement for the United States Postal Inspection Service.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] She graduated from John Randolph Tucker High School and was later a page for U.S. senator Chuck Robb.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger earned a Bachelor of Arts from the University of Virginia in 2001 and a Master of Business Administration from a joint program between the GISMA Business School in Germany and Purdue University's Krannert School of Management.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] She initially enrolled at the College of William and Mary before transferring to the University of Virginia.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] According to her sister Meredith Schatz, by the time she had completed her undergraduate degree at the University of Virginia, Spanberger was conversationally fluent in Spanish and "five or six more" languages.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] In the early 2000s, Spanberger taught English literature as a substitute teacher at the Islamic Saudi Academy in Northern Virginia.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] She received a conditional job offer from the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) in December 2002.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] While waiting for a background check to be completed, Spanberger worked as a postal inspector, as her father did, focusing on money laundering and narcotics cases.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] In July 2006, after Spanberger's background check had been completed, she joined the CIA as a case officer, working to find, recruit, and build relationships with foreign nationals who could have had information of value to the U.S. government.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] She has publicly said that she gathered intelligence about nuclear proliferation and terrorism.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Her first assignment was to Brussels, according to *The Washington Post*.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] During her career, she held, at some point, five different passports, and met people undercover.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] In 2014, Spanberger left the CIA and entered the private sector.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] She was hired by Royall & Company (now a part of EAB) to do consulting work for colleges and universities.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] After the 2016 presidential election, she began working with Emerge America to encourage women to run for state and congressional offices.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] In 2017, Virginia governor Terry McAuliffe appointed her to the Virginia Fair Housing Board.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] In July 2017, Spanberger announced her candidacy for the United States House of Representatives in Virginia's 7th congressional district in the 2018 election against incumbent Republican Dave Brat, a former Tea Party movement member.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] She had begun to consider challenging Brat after attending a town hall meeting he hosted in Nottoway County in February 2017 and made the final decision to run in May after the House voted to repeal the Affordable Care Act, texting her husband, "I'm gonna run and I'm gonna f---ing win".
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] On June 12, 2018, Spanberger defeated Dan Ward in the Democratic primary election with 73% of the vote, receiving more votes than any other candidate in the Virginia primaries that day.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] In June, after winning the primary, while waiting for a train at the Richmond Staples Mill Road Amtrak station, Spanberger met William C.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Mims, a justice on the Supreme Court of Virginia, who told her he was "impressed with her message".
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] In August, the Congressional Leadership Fund, a super PAC closely aligned with Republican House Speaker Paul Ryan, conducted a smear campaign against Spanberger.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] The campaign, which attempted to tie her to terrorism, was based on an SF-86 application she completed to obtain security clearance, which was released in breach of privacy rules.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] In a visit to the district, former Trump adviser Steve Bannon called the race "an absolute bellwether of the entire country" and said that losing it would mean Republican loss of control of the House.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger won the November 6 general election by about 6,800 votes.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Brat won eight of the district's ten counties, but Spanberger dominated the two largest counties, Henrico and Chesterfield, by a combined margin of over 30,000 votes.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] After winning the election, Virginia Supreme Court Justice Mims wrote her a letter extolling the virtues of public service, leadership, and civility, alongside a copy of former Czech President Václav Havel's essay "Politics, Morality, and Civility".
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger has said the letter and its impact on her leadership were crucial to her development as a politician.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was the first Democrat to win this seat since 1970, when four-term Democrat John Marsh retired and was succeeded by Republican J.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] But until 1993, the 7th stretched from the outer Washington suburbs through the Shenandoah Valley and Charlottesville to the outer Richmond suburbs; the present 7th is geographically and demographically the successor to what was the 3rd district before 1993.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] That district had been in Republican hands since 1981; former House majority leader Eric Cantor represented it from 2001 until Brat ousted him in the 2014 Republican primary.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger and her colleagues Elissa Slotkin and Mikie Sherrill were described as the "mod squad", a moderate alternative to the progressive "squad".
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger and Sherrill shared a Capitol Hill apartment for four years while they served in Congress together.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger faced a close reelection contest against Virginia delegate Nick Freitas, who represented much of the congressional district's northern portion.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] She won with 51% of the vote to Freitas's 49%.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Freitas carried eight of the district's ten counties, as Brat had done two years earlier, but Spanberger prevailed by winning the district's shares of Henrico and Chesterfield counties by a combined 43,400 votes, five times her overall margin of 8,400 votes.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] She was also boosted by Joe Biden narrowly carrying the district; Biden was the first Democrat to win what is now the 7th Congressional District since 1948.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] On November 5, days after winning reelection by a margin of 1.8%, Spanberger criticized the Democratic Party's strategy for the 2020 elections in a phone call with other Democratic caucus members that was subsequently leaked.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Calling the elections "a failure" from a congressional standpoint, she singled out Republican attack ads decrying "socialism" and the movement to "defund the police" as prime reasons the Democratic Party lost seats in swing districts.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger argued that Democrats should watch Republican ads before deciding how to talk about issues and never "use the word 'socialist' or 'socialism' ever again".
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] After the 2020 elections, Spanberger criticized Democratic messaging, arguing that progressive slogans such as "defund the police" and "socialism" had hurt candidates in swing districts.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] CNN political editor Chris Cillizza called her comments "hard truth" for the Democratic Party, adding that for Democrats to succeed in the 2022 and 2024 elections, they should "listen to the likes of Spanberger" rather than push for "the boldest possible progressive legislation".
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] For her first two terms, Spanberger represented a district that stretched from the Richmond suburbs to the fringes of the Shenandoah Valley.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] After the 2020 United States redistricting cycle, Spanberger's district was radically redrawn, and no longer included her home in Henrico County.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] She considered not running for reelection in the new district before deciding to do so.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was seen as one of the most vulnerable incumbents of the 2022 election cycle, with pre-election polls projecting a close race with Republican Prince William County supervisor Yesli Vega, a law enforcement officer endorsed by Governor Glenn Youngkin and former president Donald Trump.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger defeated Vega, 52% to 48%, the largest margin at the time in any election Spanberger had run in.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] According to *FiveThirtyEight*'s congressional vote tracker, Spanberger voted with President Trump 8.7% of the time.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] In the 2016 presidential election, Trump won 50% of the vote to Hillary Clinton's 44% in Spanberger's future congressional district.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] On September 23, 2019, Spanberger joined six other freshman House Democrats with national security backgrounds in calling for an impeachment inquiry into Trump.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger later announced that she would vote in favor of impeachment, saying, "The President's actions violate his oath of office, endanger our national security, and betray the public trust".
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] On June 1, 2020, Spanberger tweeted criticism of Trump's reaction to the George Floyd protests, a series of protests against police brutality that began in Minneapolis on May 26.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] On June 2, *The Washington Post* and *The New York Times* quoted Spanberger and several other high-profile former CIA analysts' interpretations of Trump's reaction to the protests as reminiscent of the reaction of totalitarian dictators on the brink of losing control of their dictatorships.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] "As a former CIA officer, I know this playbook, and I know the president's actions are betraying the very foundation of the rule of law he purports to support, the U.S.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger criticized Trump after police used tear gas and rubber bullets on peaceful protestors and a priest during the George Floyd protests to clear a path so that he could have a photo op in front of St.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger opposed Democrats' attempts to amend the Insurrection Act of 1807, saying that amending the rarely used law would not accomplish what Democrats intended.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] According to *PolitiFact*, Spanberger publicly disagreed with some of Biden's immigration policies that have not been subject to congressional votes, but she voted for all 73 bills and resolutions in the House of Representatives that Biden voiced support for.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] In December 2023, she was one of six House Democrats to send Biden a letter criticizing Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's Gaza military strategy.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] In 2020, during a meeting with then-Governor of Virginia Ralph Northam, Northam suggested she should run for governor someday.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger took his advice, and in November 2023 announced that she would not seek reelection to Congress and would instead run for governor of Virginia in the 2025 election.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] She secured the uncontested nomination in April 2025.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] In May 2025, while campaigning, Spanberger said she would not sign a bill to fully repeal Virginia's right-to-work law if elected governor.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger is one of the few Virginia gubernatorial candidates to refuse money from Dominion Energy, instead getting donations from the anti-Dominion watchdog Clean Virginia alongside her running mates, who defeated Dominion-backed candidates.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Her priorities on immigration include scrapping Youngkin's immigration order allowing local police to help carry out Trump's ICE raids and deportation policy.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] She supports rejoining the Regional Greenhouse Gas Initiative, which Youngkin, a Republican, left after Northam had joined it.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was elected in a landslide, securing 58% of the vote.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] The Republican nominee, incumbent lieutenant governor Winsome Earle-Sears, received 42%.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] It was the largest margin of victory for a Democratic gubernatorial candidate in Virginia since Albertis Harrison received just under 64% of the vote in 1961.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] The official vote margin was over 527,000.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] While Democrats won the three statewide races in Virginia in 2025, Spanberger's 15-point margin of victory was the largest.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger outperformed Kamala Harris in the 2024 presidential election in the state by nearly 10 percentage points, while winning 99% of Harris's voters.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] On November 5, Spanberger announced her transition team, which included Chris Lu, Daun Hester, and Yohannes Abraham.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Honorary co-chairs of the team included many Democratic Party of Virginia leaders, such as Louise Lucas, Don Scott, Jennifer Wexton, and Rick Boucher.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger's transition informally began on November 6 with a lunch with Governor Youngkin.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] On November 12, Spanberger asked the University of Virginia's board of visitors to pause its search for a new president until her transition was complete, drawing criticism from both Youngkin and conservative alumni of the university for supposed politicization of the board process.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger said Youngkin had done the same during his tenure, and promised structural reform to prevent it.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger made her first cabinet appointment on December 2, announcing Marvin Figueroa as Secretary of Health and Human Resources, and continued to make appointments throughout the month.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger was sworn in as governor on January 17, 2026.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] She was sworn in by former Supreme Court of Virginia Justice William C.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Mims, with her husband Adam holding the Bible and her daughters by her side.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] On January 17, 2026, her first day in office, Spanberger signed ten executive orders focusing primarily on affordability, healthcare, housing, education, and preparedness for potential federal policy changes under the Trump administration.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] One of Spanberger's first challenges as governor was managing the January 2026 North American winter storm, responsible for the deaths of four people and hundreds of traffic accidents.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] On January 30, Spanberger described the Virginia Leaders in Export Trade (VALET) program, promoting free trade in opposition to Trump's tariffs.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] The Virginia Port Authority is a major hub of international trade.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] On January 19, 2026, Spanberger delivered her first address to a joint session of the Virginia General Assembly, emphasizing affordability, bipartisanship, and pragmatic solutions.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] She committed to reentering the Regional Greenhouse Gas Initiative (RGGI), maintaining Virginia's right-to-work law, collaborating with the federal government where possible, and pushing back against policies harming Virginia jobs or families.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] She outlined legislative priorities including lowering healthcare and energy costs, protecting renters, expanding housing production, supporting agriculture amid tariffs, implementing pro-worker measures such as paid family leave and a higher minimum wage, and bipartisan gun safety bills.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Republicans welcomed the calls for unity and right-to-work commitment but proposed alternative tax relief measures and cautioned against increased spending.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger, who campaigned in support of these amendments, said she would campaign for their passage.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] HB736 limits prior authorizations for prescription medication that can lead to costly delays in care.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] On April 30, 2026, the Faith in Housing Act was signed into law.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] It eliminates the rezoning step for faith-based organizations and other tax-exempt nonprofits to develop affordable housing on their properties, allowing religious organizations to give their communities affordable housing with fewer regulatory restrictions.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] SB377 allows utilities to cooperate with high-load energy users to build new substations that exclusively serve them, at the expense of the energy user, to shield other ratepayers from increased costs incurred by their intensive consumption.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger returned the bill to the legislature with amendments on April 13, 2026.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Another amendment removed an exemption for high-load projects approved before July 1, 2026.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] The General Assembly accepted these amendments while rejecting a number of other amendments to the bill.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Shortly after taking office in January 2026, Spanberger reiterated a pledge and long-term policy goal of the state Democratic Party to rejoin the Regional Greenhouse Gas Initiative in her first address to the General Assembly.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] On April 22, to commemorate Earth Day, Spanberger signed an executive order committing Virginia to the United States Climate Alliance, a bipartisan coalition of governors committed to sustaining America's fight against climate change with state-led action.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] In May, she signed a slate of legislation aimed at preserving the state's natural resources and treating drinking water for PFAS compounds.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] On April 8, she signed into law HB507, which prohibits the Virginia Department of Environmental Quality from issuing air permits to data centers with backup diesel gen-sets that do not satisfy the Environmental Protection Agency's tier 4 emission standards.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] During her campaign, Spanberger committed to expanding the state's solar and wind energy capacity.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] On March 25, Spanberger created the cabinet-level position of Chief Energy Officer via executive order, appointing Southern Environmental Law Center attorney Josephus Allmond to the position.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] The office is tasked with cooperating with the Virginia Secretary of Commerce and Trade, the Virginia Department of Energy, PJM Interconnection, and energy utility providers to address rising energy costs, expand clean energy generation, and develop a statewide energy strategy.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] She later signed HB1444, formally codifying the Clean Energy Innovation Bank that had been trialed by the Virginia Department of Energy in 2024, which financed clean energy projects, greenhouse gas emissions reduction projects, and other similar projects.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] The recission order does not force local departments to exit existing agreements with ICE.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Nevertheless, the order has been criticized by Republicans and ICE officials, who have called it a "sanctuary state" policy that has led to an increase in immigrant crime.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] At the same time, she vetoed a law that would have prevented ICE from conducting civil arrests at courthouses, schools, and healthcare facilities.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] The Virginia House of Delegates voted to approve an amendment enshrining abortion access for all Virginia citizens shortly before Spanberger took office.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] The Senate followed suit shortly thereafter.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Spanberger signed the bill and sent it to the voters for final approval on February 6, 2026.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] On April 8, Spanberger signed the Right to Contraception Act, enshrining Virginians' right to obtain and use contraceptive drugs or devices and healthcare providers' right to provide them.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] On April 6, 2026, Spanberger signed into law HB1, which would increase the state's hourly minimum wage from $12.77 to $13.75 by January 1, 2027, and $15 by 2028; thereafter the minimum wage will be indexed to increases in the consumer price index and hiked incrementally every year.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Two days later, she signed HB20, which rescinded a statutory exemption from the state minimum wage law for farm laborers and employees, which would go into effect on January 1, 2027.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] On May 11, 2026, Spanberger signed a bill establishing a Paid Family and Medical Leave Insurance program administered by the Virginia Employment Commission, set to go into effect in 2028.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] The program will be funded by a trust fund financed by remittances from employers deducted from employee payrolls and, for employers of more than ten workers, employer contributions.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] The law extends benefits to over 1.2 million uncovered workers.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] On April 22, she signed the Equal Pay Act, which prohibits employers from querying prospective workers about their pay history and using that data in considering whether to hire them or in determining their salary unless they voluntarily provide their pay history.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] She also signed a bill that expands legal protections against wage theft.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] On June 26, 2026, Spanberger signed legislation hiking benefits for unemployment claims filed after July 5 of that year by 11.2%, from $430 to $478 per week.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] On May 14, 2026, Spanberger vetoed SB378 and HB1263, collective bargaining legislation backed by the Virginia Service Employees International Union (SEIU) and various labor groups.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] HB542 was the state legislature's most recent effort to expand the commercial sale of recreational cannabis.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] It would have established a framework for the creation of a cannabis retail market administered and regulated by the Virginia Cannabis Control Authority and partially liberalized certain restrictions on sales quantities.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] The General Assembly rejected these recommendations.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] As a result, Spanberger vetoed the bill on May 19, 2026, despite supporting the creation of a retail cannabis market as long as it had strong labeling and regulation.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] She cited the bill's "rushed timeframe", which she said gave the state too little time to design comprehensive strategies for regulating the market or to learn from the successes and errors of other states that liberalized cannabis retailing.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Negotiations continued in the following weeks, and they reached a compromise on June 16.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Semi-automatic shotguns for hunting are not considered assault weapons, and semi-automatic firearms owned before July 1 may be retained.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] The law was subject to litigation immediately after being enacted.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] She signed other restrictions relating to the possession of firearms in hospitals, the presence of polling places, and laws relating to gun owners' responsibility to keep their firearms secure.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Bypassing the commission would require another amendment to the Constitution of Virginia.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] The General Assembly can pass amendments through a majority vote by the House of Delegates and the Senate in two consecutive legislative sessions, which would send the amendment to be approved by the voters as a ballot measure.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] A corresponding resolution was adopted by the Assembly in October that allows the Virginia General Assembly to consider constitutional amendments related to redistricting during a special session, which was agreed to by the House on the 29th and by the Senate on the 31st.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Both floors reapproved the amendment after the beginning of 164th General Assembly, and Spanberger signed the legislation that sent it to the voters.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] The amendment was ultimately approved, 51.69% to 48.31%.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] It was struck down by the Supreme Court of Virginia on May 8, a ruling appealed by state Democrats.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Supreme Court rejected the appeal on May 15.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] On February 24, 2026, Spanberger delivered the Democratic response to Trump's 2026 State of the Union Address from the chamber of the House of Burgesses in the reconstructed Capitol in Williamsburg, Virginia.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Hodges* is overturned, and the Voting Rights Restoration Amendment, which restores voting rights to formerly incarcerated people who completed felony sentences.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] The 2026 legislative session concluded on March 14 with sine die adjournment without a final biennial budget agreement, due to a dispute over data center tax exemptions.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] In April 2026, Spanberger signed a bill that eliminates tax breaks for organizations related to the Confederate States of America, and a package of legislation relating to maternal healthcare and telemedicine.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Most bills would take effect on July 1, 2026.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Very early in Spanberger's governorship, opinion polls showed that her job approval rating was fairly stable and similar to the average of previous Virginia governors.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] A poll by the Institute for Policy and Opinion Research at Roanoke College in early February showed that 53% of Virginians gave her high marks for her job performance, while 38% disapproved.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] By April, her approval rating had dropped significantly, with a *Washington Post*–Schar School poll finding that 47% of voters approved of Spanberger and 46% disapproved.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] This marked the worst net approval rating for a governor in the early months of their term in *Washington Post* polls since the early 1990s.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] Similarly, a State Navigate poll conducted on April 10–13 showed her net approval rating to be breaking even.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] But after the 2026 Virginia redistricting amendment, a *Public Sentiment Institute* poll found that 52% of voters approved of Spanberger and 41% disapproved, as in earlier polls.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p01] In June 2026, *Vox* described Spanberger as polarizing, attempting to placate both businesses and Democrats, while being viewed negatively by Republicans.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger positions herself as a moderate Democrat and has called herself a "passionate pragmatist".
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] In the 2019 speaker of the United States House of Representatives election on the opening day of the 116th United States Congress, Spanberger voted for Representative Cheri Bustos, an Illinois Democrat, joining 11 other Democrats who did not back Nancy Pelosi.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, overturning the right to abortion established by *Roe v.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] Wade*, saying that "it undermines the right to privacy and a woman's right to choose".
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] She opposes legislation to restrict abortion, saying that the government should not "mandate a pregnancy".
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] During her gubernatorial campaign, Spanberger said she would support a constitutional amendment to restore "the *Roe* standard" and that she supported Virginia's existing laws requiring minors seeking abortions to receive parental consent, and certain limitations on third-trimester abortions.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] In February 2023, Spanberger was one of 12 House Democrats who voted in favor of H.J.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] 7, a Republican-sponsored resolution to terminate the national emergency concerning COVID-19 declared in March 2020.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] During her 2025 campaign for governor of Virginia, a January 6, 2021, photograph of Spanberger wearing an emergency escape hood inside the Capitol was circulated online by critics, who misrepresented it as COVID-19 protective gear and mocked her.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] In 2023, Spanberger voted against overturning the District of Columbia's revision of its criminal code, which reduced the maximum penalties for burglary, carjacking, and robbery.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger opposes defunding the police, and has supported bills that would increase the ability of local police departments to hire and train more officers.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] Although she was not a member of Congress when it passed, Spanberger criticized the 2017 Tax Cuts and Jobs Act supported by President Donald Trump, arguing that its permanent tax cuts for corporations would increase the national debt.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger called for the passage of the USMCA trade deal negotiated by the Trump administration, Mexico, and Canada.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger opposed Trump's tariffs during her 2025 gubernatorial campaign.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] She has promoted free trade during her tenure as governor.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] In May 2020, Spanberger voted against the HEROES Act, a proposed $3 trillion stimulus package in response to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] She said the bill went "far beyond" pandemic relief and had no chance of passing the Republican-controlled Senate.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] In November 2020, Spanberger led a bipartisan effort to secure the 340B Drug Pricing Program against changes that would lead to significant increases in prescription medication costs.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger supports banning members of Congress from trading stocks.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] She has introduced legislation that would require lawmakers, as well as their spouses and dependent children, to place assets in a blind trust while in office.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] In September 2025, Spanberger wrote an opinion article in *The Washington Post* opposing DOGE for conducting mass layoffs of federal workers in 2025 which particularly affect Virginia, as many federal workers live there.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger focused her 2025 gubernatorial campaign on affordability and jobs.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] Through her "Strengthening Virginia Schools Plan", Spanberger announced she would make higher education more affordable and accessible and make it easier for high school students to take college-level courses.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] She supports allowing teachers to deliver instruction and manage curriculum without interference from political bodies or agendas.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger has emphasized strengthening public schools by hiring and fairly compensating teachers, rather than supporting private schools and school choice.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger has called climate change "one of the greatest and most imminent threats to our economy, our national security, and our way of life" and said she will "stand up to attacks against science".
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] During a 2019 Committee on Foreign Affairs meeting, she asked the Trump administration to reverse its isolationist policies, saying, "it's in our national interest to reinforce our stature as a global leader on international environmental and energy issues".
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger called the Green New Deal proposed by Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez a "bold compilation of ideas meant to address global climate change" but criticized it for allegedly including unrelated policy proposals and not identifying specific resolutions to the problems that it identifies.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] "Overall I am not a supporter of the Green New Deal", she said.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] In February 2023, during the Russo–Ukrainian War, Spanberger signed a letter advocating that President Biden give Ukraine F-16 fighter jets.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] In June 2025, Spanberger supported the U.S. strikes on Iranian nuclear sites.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger has called for a new version of the Federal Assault Weapons Ban that expired in 2004.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] She favors requiring background checks on private gun sales and supported a ban on bump stocks.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] Before she served in Congress, Spanberger volunteered with Moms Demand Action, a gun-control advocacy group.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger supports the Affordable Care Act (Obamacare).
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] She supports a public option for healthcare via the proposed Medicare-X Choice Act.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] In November 2020, she called reducing the cost of prescription drugs "the top priority of families in my district".
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] In January 2020, Spanberger sponsored the Public Disclosure of Drug Discounts Act, which passed the House unanimously.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] The bill requires pharmacy benefit managers (PBMs), who manage prescription drug benefits for health insurance companies, to publicize the rebates, discounts, and price concessions they negotiate, via a website hosted by the U.S. secretary of health and human services.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger also co-sponsored the Elijah Cummings Lower Drug Costs Now Act, which grants Medicare Part D the power to negotiate prescription prices directly with drug companies.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger objected to President Trump's travel bans from certain predominantly Muslim countries and argued that they would aid jihadist propaganda by allowing a portrayal of the U.S. as an anti-Muslim country.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] She has voiced her support for stronger border security measures but opposes Trump's proposed wall.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] Spanberger voted for a bill that included funding for border infrastructure, technology at ports of entry, and more customs and border protection officers and agents.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] She said she does not support "sanctuary cities" but also called the term "a campaign slogan a lot of people get caught up in".
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] She added that it "degrades the value of the conversation if we're not actually talking about what the real concern is." Spanberger called for a pathway to legal status for illegal immigrants who abide by the laws, work, and pay taxes.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] Immigration and Customs Enforcement to be notified when undocumented immigrants attempt to purchase firearms.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] In 2022, she voted in favor of the Respect for Marriage Act.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] When Spanberger ran for governor in 2025, she was endorsed by the Human Rights Campaign, an LGBTQ advocacy group.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] In April 2006 she married Adam Spanberger, a University of Virginia-trained engineer, and her high school sweetheart.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] She helped run a Girl Scouts troop for her daughters when they were young.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] In 2014, the family moved to Henrico County.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] Before Spanberger became governor, they lived in Glen Allen, Virginia.
[src:william-branch-giles/abigail-spanberger-p02] During her time in Congress, Spanberger roomed with colleague Mikie Sherrill, who was elected governor of New Jersey on the same day Spanberger was elected governor of Virginia.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] Born to the former Elizabeth Woodson (1740–1791) and her husband Nathaniel Venable (1733–1804) at Slate Hill Plantation, a farm in what is now Worsham, Prince Edward County, then in the Colony of Virginia.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] His father operated plantations using enslaved labor, as well as represented Prince Edward County in the House of Burgesses and later in the Virginia House of Delegates, and helped found the first Presbyterian church in Prince Edward County.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] This younger Abraham Venable received a private education suitable to his class, then attended Hampden–Sydney College, which his father helped establish in 1775.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] He traveled to New Jersey for higher education at what was then the College of New Jersey (now Princeton University), and graduated in 1780.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] In addition to helping his father and overseers operate plantations in Prince Edward County, Venable studied law, but never married.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] Various members of the Venable clan owned slaves in Prince Edward County in 1787.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] However, only his eldest brother Samuel W.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] Venable (1756–1821) actually lived in Prince Edward County in 1787, having married the daughter of Judge Paul Carrington (and was taxed on 15 slaves (seven adults and eight children), four horses and 27 other livestock).
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] Venable owned eight slaves (four adults and four children) in Prince Edward County, as well as three horses and nine cattle.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] Their father Nathaniel Venable held a license to operate an ordinary (tavern/inn) in Prince Edward County and paid the taxes for William Anderson and Jessee Hamblet (probable overseers), as well as for 26 slaves (14 adults and 12 children), 8 horses and 44 other livestock.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] In the 1810 census for Prince Edward County, Abraham B.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] Venable owned 31 slaves, most of the six men with that surname in the county.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] Admitted to the bar in September 1784, Venable would come to develop a private legal practice centered at Farmville, the county seat of Prince Edward County, Virginia.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] Other members of the local bar included Richard N.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] Venable, Patrick Henry and Paul Carrington Jr. who were admitted in 1786 and 1788, respectively.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] Charles Venable was the Prince Edward County sheriff when Virginia became a Commonwealth in 1776, succeeded by Nathaniel Venable, then other men.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] Venable succeeded Robert Lawson as deputy Attorney General for the county in April 1788, and resigned the following May, succeeded by his cousin and fellow Princeton graduate, Joseph Venable.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] Charles Venable became one of the county's 22 magistrates in 1785, but he and Thomas Haskins were removed in July 1787 pursuant to a warrant from Lieutenant Governor Beverly Randolph.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] At the Virginia Ratification Convention of 1788, Patrick Henry and Robert Lawson represented Prince Edward County.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] Venable was becoming involved in politics, and won election to the Second Congress, serving from 1791 to 1799.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] There, he became chairman of the Committee on Elections in the Fourth Congress.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] After his congressional stint, Venable won election and thrice re-election as one of Prince Edward County's representative in the Virginia House of Delegates, mostly alongside Peter Johnston (who would ultimately become the body's Speaker), serving from 1801 until taking his interim U.S.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] Fellow legislators in the Virginia General Assembly elected Venable to the Senate to fill a vacancy, serving from 1803 to 1804, when he resigned (after his father's death) to practice law in Richmond.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] A friend of Thomas Jefferson, Venable helped found and became president of Bank of Virginia.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] Venable was one of the most prominent people to die in the Richmond Theatre fire in 1811.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] His ashes (and those of other victims, including Virginia Governor George William Smith) were placed under a rock at Monumental Church in Richmond.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] His brother Richard Nathaniel Venable, who had served as an officer during the Revolutionary War, would inherit Slate Hill Plantation, as well as continue the family political tradition as a lawyer, state senator and member of the Virginia Constitutional Convention of 1829.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] Their nephew Abraham Watkins Venable would also serve in the U.S.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] Congress, representing a North Carolina district.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] The family's plantation house survives and is being investigated and restored.
[src:william-branch-giles/abraham-b-venable] In 2003 a historical marker was erected.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Fulkerson was born on May 13, 1834, in Washington County, Virginia, the youngest son of Abram Fulkerson Sr.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] His family took pride in their military heritage.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] His grandfather, James Fulkerson, had also served as a Captain, in the Virginia Militia during the American Revolution, joining with the Overmountain Men and fighting the British at the Battle of Kings Mountain.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] His father, Abram Fulkerson Sr., had served during the War of 1812 as a captain of a Virginia Militia company in Colonel David Sanders' Regiment, 4th Brigade, Norfolk Division under Gen.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Porter, but by 1850 had moved to Grainger County, Tennessee, where his eldest son James L.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Fulkerson died, although Abram Fulkerson Sr. moved back to Washington County, Virginia, before his death in 1859.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] The family included at least four more sons who survived to adulthood: James Lyon Fulkerson (1816–1849), Samuel Vance Fulkerson (1822–1862), Francis Marion Fulkerson (1825–1894) and Isaac Fulkerson (1831–1889).
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] They also had daughters Mary Vance Fulkerson Davis (1820–1892), Harriet Jane Fulkerson Armstrong (1827–1911) and Katherine Elizabeth Fulkerson (1832–1903).
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Abram Jr. graduated from the Virginia Military Institute at Lexington in 1857, where he was a student of Prof.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Thomas Jonathan Stonewall Jackson, as had been his elder brother Samuel Vance Fulkerson (1822–1862), who had served in the Mexican–American War and as a delegate to the Virginia Constitutional Convention of 1850.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] According to VMI records, Isaac Fulkerson had a reputation for being a prankster and wore an "outlandish collar" on his cadet uniform: the collar being the only part of the uniform not covered under regulations.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] After graduation, he taught school in Palmyra, Virginia, then in 1860 in Rogersville, Hawkins County, Tennessee.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Fulkerson entered Confederate military service in June 1861 as a Captain, having organized a company of men from Hawkins County, Tennessee, that was mustered into the 19th Tennessee Infantry Regiment as Company K (The Hawkins Boys) at Knoxville, Tennessee.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] His was the first company of volunteers organized in East Tennessee, and Abram Fulkerson received a commission as the regiment's Major.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] He was wounded in the thigh and his horse shot from under him at the Battle of Shiloh.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] After recovery and the unit's reorganization, he was reassigned to the 63rd Tennessee Infantry.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Commissioned as Lieutenant Colonel of the 63rd, and President Jefferson Davis on February 12, 1864, commissioned him as a full colonel.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] In January 1862, Abram Fulkerson received a furlough and went to Clarksville, Tennessee, and married his fiancé, Selina Johnson (1832–1918) on January 28.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] They were barely married in time to escape the Union Army's advance on Clarksville.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Samuel Vance Fulkerson was killed in action leading the 37th Virginia Infantry at the Battle of Gaines Mill, the first major victory of General Robert E.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] 1829 – July 20, 1889), was a captain in the 8th Texas Cavalry (Terry's Texas Rangers).
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Abram Fulkerson twice helped garrison the Cumberland Gap: first with the 19th Tennessee then with the 63rd Tennessee.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] While in the 63rd, Fulkerson was wounded twice more: in the left arm at the Battle of Chickamauga and again at the Second Battle of Petersburg, Virginia (Battle of Petersburg II), the regiment having been reassigned from the Army of Tennessee to the Army of Northern Virginia.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] He was taken prisoner on June 17, 1864, and sent to the POW camp at Fort Delaware.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] On April 18, 1892, Fulkerson wrote an account of his capture and experiences as a prisoner.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Though none of the Immortal Six Hundred were killed by the continuing Confederate artillery fire from Fort Sumter, 14 died of dysentery.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] After Morris Island, Fulkerson was taken to Fort Pulaski and placed on starvation rations for 42 days in retaliation for Confederate prisoner abuses at Andersonville.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Crowded into the fort's cold, damp casements, the Confederates' "retaliation ration" consisted of 10 ounces of moldy cornmeal and a half pint of soured onion pickles.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] The starving men supplemented their rations with the occasional rat or stray cat.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Thirteen men died there of preventable diseases such as dysentery and scurvy.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] At Fort Pulaski, the prisoners organized "The Relief Association of Fort Pulaski for Aid and Relief of the Sick and Less Fortunate Prisoners" on December 13, 1864, and Fulkerson was elected president.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Out of their sparse funds, the prisoners collected and spent eleven dollars, according to a report filed by Fulkerson on December 28, 1864.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] In March 1865 Fulkerson was returned to Fort Delaware, where he was discharged and paroled on July 25, 1865, months after General Robert E.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] While at Fort Delaware, prisoners were taken out to the badly polluted river every day and allowed to bathe and swim.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Fulkerson, a very thin man with auburn hair, could float "like a cork" and would lie on his back and float out with the current for ten or fifteen minutes until the nervous guards, fearing that an escape attempt, ordered him to return to the shore.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] After Fulkerson returned home, his horse that he rode during his military service, whose official name was "Zollicoffer" (after former Congressman and early Confederate casualty Felix Zollicoffer), was returned to him.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Fulkerson kept the horse for the rest of its life, but called him "Old Bob." When the horse died, former Confederates from the Bristol area assembled and conducted a military funeral for it.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] In 1885, Stonewall Jackson's horse, "Little Sorrel," was brought to Bristol on a tour and Fulkerson rode it as a number of former veterans assembled to pay their respects.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] As the war ended, Fulkerson studied law, was admitted to the bar and began his legal practice in Goodson, later known as Bristol, Virginia, in 1866 with the firm of York & Fulkerson.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] As a lawyer, he was regarded as a legal giant in Bristol and it is said that he was such a gifted orator that many of the local citizens would go to court and sit in on trials just to hear him speak.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Fulkerson was elected and re-elected to the Virginia House of Delegates as one of two delegates representing Washington County, Virginia (part-time).
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] He served from 1871 to 1875, until voters replaced both delegates.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Next he served in the State senate of Virginia 1877–1881.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Voters from Virginia's 9th congressional district elected Fulkerson as a Readjuster Democrat from to the Forty-seventh Congress (March 4, 1881 – March 3, 1883).
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] He defeating incumbent James Buchanan Richmond, a lawyer and banker (and former subordinate officer to his brother Samuel in the 37th Virginia), in the Democratic primary.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Fulkerson helped organize the Readjuster Party, after which he returned to the Democratic Party.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Fulkerson resumed his legal practice after deciding against seeking re-election to Congress.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Fellow Readjuster Henry Bowen succeeded him.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Voters again elected Fulkerson to the State House of Delegates in 1888, alongside John A.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Buchanan who together replaced Daniel Trigg and Jonas S.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Kelly and were in turn replaced in 1887 by John Roberts and S.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] After retiring from politics, Fulkerson wrote a memoir of his captivity and published it in 1894.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Fulkerson was a delegate to the Democratic National (Gold) Convention in 1896.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Fulkerson died in Bristol, Virginia, on December 17, 1902, at the age of 68, of complications after suffering a stroke.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Henry Clinton Wood who served as the Major of the 37th Virginia Infantry (CS) under Fulkerson's brother Samuel Vance, and for whom the town of Clintwood, Virginia, was named, served as an honorary pallbearer in the funeral.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] His widow would survive for a decade, and his son Samuel Vance Fulkerson (1863–1926), although he married in Grayson, Texas, would become a Virginia lawyer and die aged 64 in Virginia Beach on July 2, 1926, and be buried in the same cemetery, East Hill Cemetery.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] VMI maintains the Fulkerson family papers in its library's archives.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] The Sons of Confederate Veterans Abram Fulkerson Camp 2104 in Greeley, Colorado, bears his name.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] His descendant third cousin, Joe Adkins, portrays Fulkerson at Civil War reenactments.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] A member of the Sons of Confederate Veterans, Adkins commands the Gen.
[src:william-branch-giles/abram-fulkerson] Jackson Camp 2159 in Jonesborough, Tennessee.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Some scholars suggest that agrarianism espouses the superiority of rural society to urban society and the independent farmer as superior to the paid worker, and sees farming as a way of life that can shape the ideal social values.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] It stresses the superiority of a simpler rural life in comparison to the complexity of urban life.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The philosophical roots of agrarianism include European and Chinese philosophers.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The Chinese school of Agriculturalism (农家/農家) was a philosophy that advocated peasant utopian communalism and egalitarianism.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In societies influenced by Confucianism that had as its foundation that humans are innately good, the farmer was considered an esteemed productive member of society, but merchants who made money were looked down upon.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] That influenced European intellectuals like François Quesnay, an avid Confucianist and advocate of China's agrarian policies, in forming the French agrarian philosophy of physiocracy.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The physiocrats, along with the ideas of John Locke and the Romantic Era, formed the basis of modern European and American agrarianism.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] , du Pont advocated low tariffs and free trade.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Physiocracy (French: *physiocratie*; from the Greek for "government of nature") is an economic theory developed by a group of 18th-century Age of Enlightenment French economists.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] They believed that the wealth of nations derived solely from the value of "land agriculture" or "land development" and that agricultural products should be highly priced.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Their theories originated in France and were most popular during the second half of the 18th century.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Physiocracy became one of the first well-developed theories of economics.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] François Quesnay (1694–1774), the Marquis de Mirabeau (1715–1789) and Anne-Robert-Jacques Turgot (1727–1781) dominated the movement, which immediately preceded the first modern school, classical economics, which began with the publication of Adam Smith's *The Wealth of Nations* in 1776.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The physiocrats made a significant contribution in their emphasis on productive work as the source of national wealth.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] This contrasted with earlier schools, in particular mercantilism, which often focused on the ruler's wealth, accumulation of gold, or the balance of trade.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] For the physiocrats, however, only agricultural labor created this value in the products of society.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] All "industrial" and non-agricultural labors were "unproductive appendages" to agricultural labor.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Quesnay was likely influenced by his medical training, particularly by the work of William Harvey who explained how blood flow and the circulatory system is vital to the human body; Quesnay held that the circulation of wealth was vital to the economy.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Societies at the time were also overwhelmingly agrarian.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] This may be why they viewed agriculture as the primary source of a nation's wealth.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] This is an idea that Quesnay purported to demonstrate with data, comparing a workshop to a farm.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] He analyzed "how money flowed between the three classes of farmers, proprietors, and artisans, in the same mechanical way that blood flows between different organs" and claimed only the farm produced a surplus that added to the nation's wealth.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Physiocrats viewed the production of goods and services as equivalent to the consumption of the agricultural surplus, since human or animal muscle provided the main source of power and all energy derived from the surplus from agricultural production.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Profit in capitalist production was really only the "rent" obtained by the owner of the land on which the agricultural production took place.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] "The physiocrats damned cities for their artificiality and praised what they considered to be more natural styles of living.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] They celebrated farmers." They called themselves *les Économistes*, but are generally referred to as "physiocrats" to distinguish their beliefs from the many schools of economic thought that followed.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The United States president Thomas Jefferson was an agrarian who based his ideas about the budding American democracy around the notion that farmers are "the most valuable citizens" and the truest republicans.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Jefferson and his support base were committed to American republicanism, which they saw as being in opposition to monarchy, aristocracy, clericalism and corruption, and which prioritized morality and virtue, exemplified by the "yeoman farmer", "planters", and the "plain folk".
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In praising the rural farmfolk, the Jeffersonians felt that financiers, bankers and industrialists created "cesspools of corruption" in the cities and should thus be avoided.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The Jeffersonians sought to align the American economy more with agriculture than industry.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Part of their motive to do so was Jefferson's fear that the over-industrialization of America would create a class of wage slaves who relied on their employers for income and sustenance.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In turn, these workers would cease to be independent voters as their vote could be manipulated by said employers.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] There is general agreement that the substantial United States' federal policy of offering land grants (such as thousands of gifts of land to veterans) had a positive impact on economic development in the 19th century.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Agrarian socialism is a form of agrarianism that is anti-capitalist in nature and seeks to introduce socialist economic systems in their stead.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Notable agrarian socialists include Emiliano Zapata who was a leading figure in the Mexican Revolution.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] As part of the Liberation Army of the South, his group of revolutionaries fought on behalf of the Mexican peasants, whom they saw as exploited by the landowning classes.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Zapata published the Plan of Ayala, which called for significant land reforms and land redistribution in Mexico as part of the revolution.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Zapata was killed and his forces crushed over the course of the Revolution, but his political ideas lived on in the form of Zapatismo.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Zapatismo would form the basis for neozapatismo, the ideology of the Zapatista Army of National Liberation.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Known as *Ejército Zapatista de Liberación Nacional* or EZLN in Spanish, EZLN is a far-left libertarian socialist political and militant group that emerged in the state of Chiapas in southmost Mexico in 1994.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] EZLN and Neozapatismo, as explicit in their name, seek to revive the agrarian socialist movement of Zapata, but fuse it with new elements such as a commitment to indigenous rights and community-level decision making.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Maoism, the far-left ideology of Mao Zedong and his followers, places a heavy emphasis on the role of peasants in its goals.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In contrast to other Marxist schools of thought which normally seek to acquire the support of urban workers, Maoism sees the peasantry as key.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] During the Chinese Civil War and the Second Sino-Japanese War, Mao and the Chinese Communist Party made extensive use of peasants and rural bases in their military tactics, often eschewing the cities.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Following the eventual victory of the Communist Party in both wars, the countryside and how it should be run remained a focus for Mao.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In 1958, Mao launched the Great Leap Forward, a social and economic campaign which, amongst other things, altered many aspects of rural Chinese life.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] It introduced mandatory collective farming and forced the peasantry to organize itself into communal living units which were known as people's communes.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] These communes, which consisted of 5,000 people on average, were expected to meet high production quotas while the peasants who lived on them adapted to this radically new way of life.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The communes were run as co-operatives where wages and money were replaced by work points.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Peasants who criticised this new system were persecuted as "rightists" and "counter-revolutionaries".
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Leaving the communes was forbidden and escaping from them was difficult or impossible, and those who attempted it were subjected to party-orchestrated "public struggle sessions," which further jeopardized their survival.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] These public criticism sessions were often used to intimidate the peasants into obeying local officials and they often devolved into little more than public beatings.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] On the communes, experiments were conducted in order to find new methods of planting crops, efforts were made to construct new irrigation systems on a massive scale, and the communes were all encouraged to produce steel backyard furnaces as part of an effort to increase steel production.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Similarly, the experimentation with the crops did not produce results.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In addition to this the Four Pests Campaign was launched, in which the peasants were called upon to destroy sparrows and other wild birds that ate crop seeds, in order to protect fields.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Pest birds were shot down or scared away from landing until they dropped from exhaustion.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] This campaign resulted in an ecological disaster that saw an explosion of the vermin population, especially crop-eating insects, which was consequently not in danger of being killed by predators.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] None of these new systems were working, but local leaders did not dare to state this, instead, they falsified reports so as not to be punished for failing to meet the quotas.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In many cases they stated that they were greatly exceeding their quotas, and in turn, the Chinese state developed a completely false sense of success with regard to the commune system.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] All of this culminated in the Great Chinese Famine, which began in 1959, lasted 3 years, and saw an estimated 15 to 30 million Chinese people die.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] A combination of bad weather and the new, failed farming techniques that were introduced by the state led to massive shortages of food.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] By 1962, the Great Leap Forward was declared to be at an end.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In the late 1960s and early 1970s, Mao once again radically altered life in rural China with the launching of the Down to the Countryside Movement.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] As a response to the Great Chinese Famine, the Chinese President Liu Shaoqi began "sending down" urban youths to rural China in order to recover its population losses and alleviate overcrowding in the cities.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] However, Mao turned the practice into a political crusade, declaring that the sending down would strip the youth of any bourgeois tendencies by forcing them to learn from the unprivileged rural peasants.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In reality, it was the Communist Party's attempt to reign in the Red Guards, who had become uncontrollable during the course of the Cultural Revolution.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] 10% of the 1970 urban population of China was sent out to remote rural villages, often in Inner Mongolia.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The villages, which were still poorly recovering from the effects of the Great Chinese Famine, did not have the excess resources that were needed to support the newcomers.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Furthermore, the so-called "sent-down youth" had no agricultural experience and as a result, they were unaccustomed to the harsh lifestyle that existed in the countryside, and their unskilled labor in the villages provided little benefit to the agricultural sector.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] As a result, many of the sent-down youth died in the countryside.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The relocation of the youths was originally intended to be permanent, but by the end of the Cultural Revolution, the Communist Party relented and some of those who had the capacity to return to the cities were allowed to do so.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In imitation of Mao's policies, the Khmer Rouge of Cambodia (who were heavily funded and supported by the People's Republic of China) created their own version of the Great Leap Forward which was known as "Maha Lout Ploh".
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] With the Great Leap Forward as its model, it had similarly disastrous effects, contributing to what is now known as the Cambodian genocide.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] As a part of the Maha Lout Ploh, the Khmer Rouge sought to create an entirely agrarian socialist society by forcibly relocating 100,000 people to move from Cambodia's cities into newly created communes.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The Khmer Rouge leader, Pol Pot sought to "purify" the country by setting it back to "Year Zero", freeing it from "corrupting influences".
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Besides trying to completely de-urbanize Cambodia, ethnic minorities were slaughtered along with anyone else who was suspected of being a "reactionary" or a member of the "bourgeoisie", to the point that wearing glasses was seen as grounds for execution.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The killings were only brought to an end when Cambodia was invaded by the neighboring socialist nation of Vietnam, whose army toppled the Khmer Rouge.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] However, with Cambodia's entire society and economy in disarray, including its agricultural sector, the country still plunged into renewed famine due to vast food shortages.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] However, as international journalists began to report on the situation and send images of it out to the world, a massive international response was provoked, leading to one of the most concentrated relief efforts of its time.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Peasant parties first appeared across Eastern Europe between 1860 and 1910, when commercialized agriculture and world market forces disrupted traditional rural society, and the railway and growing literacy facilitated the work of roving organizers.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Agrarian parties advocated land reforms to redistribute land on large estates among those who work it.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] They also wanted village cooperatives to keep the profit from crop sales in local hands and credit institutions to underwrite needed improvements.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Many peasant parties were also nationalist parties because peasants often worked their land for the benefit of landlords of different ethnicity.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Peasant parties rarely had any power before World War I but some became influential in the interwar era, especially in Bulgaria and Czechoslovakia.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] For a while, in the 1920s and the 1930s, there was a Green International (International Agrarian Bureau) based on the peasant parties in Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia, Poland, and Serbia.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] It functioned primarily as an information center that spread the ideas of agrarianism and combating socialism on the left and landlords on the right and never launched any significant activities.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In Bulgaria, the Bulgarian Agrarian National Union (BZNS) was organized in 1899 to resist taxes and build cooperatives.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] BZNS came to power in 1919 and introduced many economic, social, and legal reforms.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] However, conservative forces crushed BZNS in a 1923 coup and assassinated its leader, Aleksandar Stamboliyski (1879–1923).
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] BZNS was made into a communist puppet group until 1989, when it reorganized as a genuine party.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In Czechoslovakia, the Republican Party of Agricultural and Smallholder People often shared power in parliament as a partner in the five-party pětka coalition.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The party's leader, Antonín Švehla (1873–1933), was prime minister several times.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] It was consistently the strongest party, forming and dominating coalitions.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] It moved beyond its original agrarian base to reach middle-class voters.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The party was banned by the National Front after the Second World War.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In France, the Hunting, Fishing, Nature, Tradition party is a moderate conservative, agrarian party, reaching a peak of 4.23% in the 2002 French presidential election.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] It would later on become affiliated to France's main conservative party, Union for a Popular Movement.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] More recently, the Resistons! movement of Jean Lassalle espoused agrarianism.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In Hungary, the first major agrarian party, the small-holders party was founded in 1908.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The party became part of the government in the 1920s but lost influence in the government.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] A new party, the Independent Smallholders, Agrarian Workers and Civic Party was established in 1930 with a more radical program representing larger scale land redistribution initiatives.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] They implemented this program together with the other coalition parties after WWII.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] However, after 1949 the party was outlawed when a one-party system was introduced.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] They became part of the government again 1990–1994, and 1998–2002 after which they lost political support.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The ruling Fidesz party has an agrarian faction, and promotes agrarian interest since 2010 with the emphasis now placed on supporting larger family farms versus small-holders.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In the late 19th century, the Irish National Land League aimed to abolish landlordism in Ireland and enable tenant farmers to own the land they worked on.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The "Land War" of 1878–1909 led to the Irish Land Acts, ending absentee landlords and ground rent and redistributing land among peasant farmers.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Post-independence, the Farmers' Party operated in the Irish Free State from 1922, folding into the National Centre Party in 1932.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] It was mostly supported by wealthy farmers in the east of Ireland.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Clann na Talmhan (Family of the Land; also called the *National Agricultural Party*) was founded in 1938.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] They focused more on the poor smallholders of the west, supporting land reclamation, afforestation, social democracy and rates reform.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] They formed part of the governing coalition of the Government of the 13th Dáil and Government of the 15th Dáil.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Economic improvement in the 1960s saw farmers vote for other parties and Clann na Talmhan disbanded in 1965.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In Kazakhstan, the Peasants' Union, originally a communist organization, was formed as one of first agrarian parties in independent Kazakhstan and would win four seats in the 1994 legislative election.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The Agrarian Party of Kazakhstan, led by Romin Madinov, was founded in 1999, which favored the privatization of agricultural land, developments towards rural infrastructure, as well as changes in the tax system in agrarian economy.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] From there, the bloc remained short-lived as it would merge with the ruling Nur Otan party in 2006.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Several other parties in Kazakhstan over the years have embraced agrarian policies in their programs in an effort to appeal towards a large rural Kazakh demographic base, which included Amanat, ADAL, and Respublica.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Since late 2000s, the Auyl party remains the largest and most influential agrarian-oriented party in Kazakhstan, as its presidential candidate Jiguli Dairabaev had become the second-place frontrunner in the 2022 presidential election after sweeping 3.4% of the vote.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In the 2023 legislative election, the Auyl party for the first time was represented the parliament after winning nine seats in the lower chamber Mäjilis.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The party raises rural issues in regard to decaying villages, rural development and the agro-industrial complex, the issues of social security of the rural population, and has consistently opposed the ongoing rural flight in Kazakhstan.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In Latvia, the Union of Greens and Farmers is supportive of traditional small farms and perceives them as more environmentally friendly than large-scale farming: Nature is threatened by development, while small farms are threatened by large industrial-scale farms.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In Lithuania, the government led by the Lithuanian Farmers and Greens Union was in power between 2016 and 2020.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The Nordic agrarian parties, also referred to as Scandinavian agrarian parties or agrarian liberal parties, are agrarian political parties that belong to a political tradition particular to the Nordic countries.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Positioning themselves in the centre of the political spectrum, but fulfilling roles distinctive to Nordic countries, they remain hard to classify by conventional political ideology.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] These parties are non-Socialist and typically combine a commitment to small businesses, rural issues and political decentralisation, and, at times, scepticism towards the European Union.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The parties have divergent views on the free market and environmentalism.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Internationally, they are most commonly aligned to the Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe (ALDE) and the Liberal International.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Historically farmers' parties, a declining farmer population after the Second World War made them broaden their scope to other issues and sections of society.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] At this time three of them renamed themselves to Centre Party, with the Finnish Centre Party being the last to do so, in 1965.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In the modern period, the main agrarian parties are the Centre Party in Sweden, *Venstre* in Denmark, Centre Party in Finland, Centre Party in Norway and Progressive Party in Iceland.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In Poland, the Polish People's Party (*Polskie Stronnictwo Ludowe*, PSL) traces its tradition to an agrarian party in Austro-Hungarian-controlled Galician Poland.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] After the fall of the communist regime, PSL's biggest success came in 1993 elections, where it won 132 out of 460 parliamentary seats.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Since then, PSL's support has steadily declined, until 2019, when they formed Polish Coalition with an anti-establishment, direct democracy Kukiz'15 party, and managed to get 8.5% of popular vote.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Moreover, PSL tends to get much better results in local elections.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In 2014 elections they have managed to get 23.88% of votes.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The right-wing Law and Justice party has also become supportive of agrarian policies in recent years and polls show that most of their support comes from rural areas.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] AGROunia resembles the features of agrarianism.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In Romania, older party parties from Transylvania, Moldavia, and Wallachia merged to become the National Peasants' Party (PNȚ) in 1926.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Iuliu Maniu (1873–1953) was a prime minister with an agrarian cabinet from 1928 to 1930 and briefly in 1932–1933, but the Great Depression made proposed reforms impossible.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The communist administration dissolved the party in 1947 (along with other historical parties such as the National Liberal Party), but it reformed in 1989 after they fell from power.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The reformed party, which also incorporated elements of Christian democracy in its ideology, governed Romania as part of the Romanian Democratic Convention (CDR) between 1996 and 2000.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In Serbia, Nikola Pašić (1845–1926) and his People's Radical Party dominated Serbian politics after 1903.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The party also monopolized power in Yugoslavia from 1918 to 1929.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] During the dictatorship of the 1930s, the prime minister was from that party.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In Ukraine, the Radical Party of Oleh Lyashko has promised to purify the country of oligarchs "with a pitchfork".
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In land law the heyday of English, Irish (and thus Welsh) agrarianism was c.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The heyday was eroded by hundreds of Acts of Parliament to expressly permit enclosure, chiefly from 1650 to the 1810s.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Politicians standing strongly as reactionaries to this included the Levellers, those anti-industrialists (Luddites) going beyond opposing new weaving technology and, later, radicals such as William Cobbett.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] A high level of net national or local self-sufficiency has a strong base in campaigns and movements.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In the 19th century such empowered advocates included Peelites and most Conservatives.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The 21st century has seen decarbonisation already in electricity markets.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Following protests and charitable lobbying local food has seen growing market share, sometimes backed by wording in public policy papers and manifestos.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The UK has many sustainability-prioritising businesses, green charity campaigns, events and lobby groups ranging from espousing allotment gardens (hobby community farming) through to a clear policy of local food and/or self-sustainability models.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The National Party of Australia (formerly called the Country Party), from the 1920s to the 1970s, promulgated its version of agrarianism, which it called "countrymindedness".
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The goal was to enhance the status of the graziers (operators of big sheep stations) and small farmers and justified subsidies for them.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The New Zealand Liberal Party aggressively promoted agrarianism in its heyday (1891–1912).
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The landed gentry and aristocracy ruled Britain at this time.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] New Zealand never had an aristocracy but its wealthy landowners largely controlled politics before 1891.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The Liberal Party set out to change that by a policy it called "populism." Richard Seddon had proclaimed the goal as early as 1884: "It is the rich and the poor; it is the wealthy and the landowners against the middle and labouring classes.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] That, Sir, shows the real political position of New Zealand." The Liberal strategy was to create a large class of small landowning farmers who supported Liberal ideals.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The Liberal government also established the basis of the later welfare state such as old age pensions and developed a system for settling industrial disputes, which was accepted by both employers and trade unions.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] In 1893, it extended voting rights to women, making New Zealand the first country in the world to do so.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] To obtain land for farmers, the Liberal government from 1891 to 1911 purchased 3,100,000 acres (1,300,000 ha) of Maori land.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The government also purchased 1,300,000 acres (530,000 ha) from large estate holders for subdivision and closer settlement by small farmers.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The Advances to Settlers Act (1894) provided low-interest mortgages, and the agriculture department disseminated information on the best farming methods.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The Liberals proclaimed success in forging an egalitarian, anti-monopoly land policy.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The policy built up support for the Liberal Party in rural North Island electorates.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] By 1903, the Liberals were so dominant that there was no longer an organized opposition in Parliament.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The United States and Canada both saw a rise of Agrarian-oriented parties in the early twentieth century as economic troubles motivated farming communities to become politically active.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] It has been proposed that different responses to agrarian protest largely determined the course of power generated by these newly energized rural factions.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] These reactions may have helped determine the outcome of agrarian power and political associations in the US and Canada.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Economic desperation experienced by farmers across the state of Kansas in the nineteenth century spurred the creation of The People's Party in 1890, and soon-after would gain control of the governor's office in 1892.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] This party, consisting of a mix of Democrats, Socialists, Populists, and Fusionists, would find itself buckling from internal conflict regarding the unlimited coinage of silver.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] The Populists permanently lost power in 1898.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Oklahoma farmers considered their political activity during the early twentieth century due to the outbreak of war, depressed crop prices, and an inhibited sense of progression towards owning their own farms.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Tenancy had been reportedly as high as 55% in Oklahoma by 1910.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] This agrarian-backed Socialist party would win numerous offices, causing a panic within the local Democratic party.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] This agrarian-Socialist movement would be inhibited by voter suppression laws aimed at reducing the participation of voters of color, as well as national wartime policies intended to disrupt political elements considered subversive.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] During the 1930s and 1940s many farmers supported the Wisconsin Progressive Party - National Progressives.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Agrarianism during this time was often linked with progressive politics.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Agrarianism is similar to but not identical with the back-to-the-land movement.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Agrarianism concentrates on the fundamental goods of the earth, on communities of more limited economic and political scale than in modern society, and on simple living, even when the shift involves questioning the "progressive" character of some recent social and economic developments.
[src:william-branch-giles/agrarianism] Thus, agrarianism is not industrial farming, with its specialization on products and industrial scale.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin was born in Geneva in present-day Switzerland and spoke French as a first language.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Inspired by the ideals of the American Revolution, he immigrated to the United States in the 1780s, settling in western Pennsylvania.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] He served as a delegate to the 1789 Pennsylvania Constitutional Convention and won election to the Pennsylvania General Assembly.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Senate in 1793, emerging as a leading Anti-Federalist and opponent of Alexander Hamilton's economic policies.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] However, he was soon removed from office on a party-line vote due to not meeting requisite citizenship requirements; returning to Pennsylvania, Gallatin helped calm many angry farmers during the Whiskey Rebellion.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] House of Representatives in 1795, where he helped establish the House Ways and Means Committee.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] He became the chief spokesman on financial matters for the Democratic-Republican Party and led opposition to the Federalist economic program.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin helped Thomas Jefferson prevail in the contentious 1800 U.S. presidential election, and his reputation as a prudent financial manager led to his appointment as Treasury Secretary.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Under Jefferson, Gallatin reduced government spending, instituted checks and balances for government expenditures, and financed the Louisiana Purchase and advocated for internal improvements, most notably through his *Report on Roads and Canals*.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] He retained his position through James Madison's administration until February 1814, maintaining much of Hamilton's financial system while presiding over a reduction in the national debt.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin served on the American commission that agreed to the Treaty of Ghent, which ended the War of 1812.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In the aftermath of the war, he helped found the Second Bank of the United States.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Declining another term at the Treasury, Gallatin served as U.S.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Ambassador to France from 1816 to 1823, struggling with scant success to improve relations during the Bourbon Restoration.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In the 1824 U.S. presidential election, Gallatin was nominated for Vice President by the Democratic-Republican Congressional caucus but never wanted the position and ultimately withdrew due to a lack of popular support.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In 1826 and 1827, he served as the American ambassador to Britain and negotiated several agreements, such as a ten-year extension of the joint occupation of Oregon Country.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] He thereafter retired from politics and dedicated the rest of his life to various civic, humanitarian, and academic causes.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin was born on January 29, 1761, in Geneva, and was until 1785 a citizen of the Republic of Geneva.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] His parents were the wealthy Jean Gallatin and his wife Sophie Albertine Rollaz.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin's family had great influence in the Republic of Geneva, and many family members held distinguished positions in the magistracy and the army.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Jean Gallatin, a prosperous merchant, died in 1765, followed by Sophie in April 1770.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Now orphaned, Gallatin was taken into the care of Mademoiselle Pictet, a family friend and distant relative of Gallatin's father.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In January 1773, Gallatin was sent to study at the elite Academy of Geneva.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] While attending the academy, Gallatin read deeply the philosophy of Jean-Jacques Rousseau and Voltaire, along with the French Physiocrats; he became dissatisfied with the traditionalism of Geneva.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] A student of the Enlightenment, he believed in the nobility of human nature and that when freed from social restrictions, it would display admirable qualities and greater results in both the physical and the moral world.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] The democratic spirit of the United States attracted him and he decided to emigrate.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In April 1780, Gallatin secretly left Geneva with his classmate Henri Serre.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Carrying letters of recommendation from eminent Americans (including Benjamin Franklin) that the Gallatin family procured, the young men left France in May, sailing on an American ship, "the Kattie".
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] They reached Cape Ann on July 14 and arrived in Boston the next day, traveling the intervening thirty miles by horseback.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Bored with monotonous Bostonian life, Gallatin and Serre set sail with a Swiss female companion to the settlement of Machias, located on the northeastern tip of the Maine frontier.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] At Machias, Gallatin operated a bartering venture, in which he dealt with a variety of goods and supplies.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] He enjoyed the simple life and the natural environment surrounding him.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin and Serre returned to Boston in October 1781 after abandoning their bartering venture in Machias.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Friends of Pictet, who had learned that Gallatin had traveled to the United States, convinced Harvard College to employ Gallatin as a French tutor.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin disliked living in New England, instead preferring to become a farmer in the Trans-Appalachian West, which at that point was the frontier of American settlement.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] He became the interpreter and business partner of a French land speculator, Jean Savary, and traveled throughout various parts of the United States in order to purchase undeveloped Western lands.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In 1785, he became an American citizen after he swore allegiance to the state of Virginia, fulfilling the requirements of citizenship as established under Article IV of the Articles of Confederation.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin inherited a significant sum of money the following year, and he used that money to purchase a 400-acre plot of land in Fayette County, Pennsylvania.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] He built a stone house named Friendship Hill on the new property.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin co-founded a company designed to attract Swiss settlers to the United States, but the company proved unable to attract many settlers.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In 1789, Gallatin married Sophie Allègre, the daughter of a Richmond boardinghouse owner, but Allègre died just five months into the marriage.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] He was in mourning for a number of years and seriously considered returning to Geneva.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] However, on November 1, 1793, he married Hannah Nicholson, daughter of the well-connected Commodore James Nicholson.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] They had two sons and four daughters: Catherine, Sophia Albertine, Hannah Maria, Frances, James, and Albert Rolaz Gallatin.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Catherine died of whooping cough and the measles before she was eight months old, Sophia and Hannah also died as infants.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin's marriage proved to be politically and economically advantageous, as the Nicholsons enjoyed connections in New York, Georgia, and Maryland.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] With most of his business ventures unsuccessful, Gallatin sold much of his land, excluding Friendship Hill, to Robert Morris; he and his wife would instead live in Philadelphia and other coastal cities for most of the rest of their lives.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In 1788, Gallatin was elected as a delegate to a state convention to discuss possible revisions to the United States Constitution.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In the next two years, he served as a delegate to a state constitutional convention.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] He won election to the Pennsylvania House of Representatives and served from 1790 to 1792.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] As a public official, he aligned with Anti-Federalists and spent much of his time in the state and national capital of Philadelphia.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] His service on the Ways and Means Committee earned him a strong reputation as an expert in finance and taxation.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin won election to the United States Senate in early 1793, and he took his seat in December of that year.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] He quickly emerged as a prominent opponent of Alexander Hamilton's economic program but was declared ineligible for a seat in the Senate in February 1794 because he had not been a citizen for the required nine years prior to election.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] The dispute itself had important ramifications.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] At the time, the Senate held closed sessions.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] However, with the American Revolution only a decade ended, the senators were leery of anything which might hint that they intended to establish an aristocracy, so they opened up their chamber for the first time for the debate over whether to unseat Gallatin.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Soon after, open sessions became standard procedure for the Senate.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin was one of two senators to vote against the Eleventh Amendment to the United States Constitution.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin had strongly opposed the 1791 establishment of an excise tax on whiskey, as whiskey trade and production constituted an important part of the Western economy.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In 1794, after Gallatin had been removed from the Senate and returned to Friendship Hill, the Whiskey Rebellion broke out among disgruntled farmers opposed to the federal collection of the whiskey tax.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin did not join in the rebellion, but criticized the military response of the President George Washington's administration as an overreaction.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In the aftermath of the Whiskey Rebellion, Gallatin won election to the United States House of Representatives, taking his seat in March 1795.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Upon his return to Congress, Gallatin became the leading financial expert of the Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In 1796, Gallatin published *A Sketch on the Finances of the United States*, which discussed the operations of the Treasury Department and strongly attacked the Federalist Party's financial program.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Some historians and biographers believe that Gallatin founded the House Ways and Means Committee in order to check Hamilton's influence over financial issues, but historian Patrick Furlong argues that Hamilton's Federalist allies were actually responsible for founding the committee.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] After James Madison declined to seek re-election in 1796, Gallatin emerged as the Democratic-Republican leader in the House of Representatives.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] During the Quasi-War with France, Gallatin criticized military expenditures and opposed passage of the Alien and Sedition Acts.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In the contingent election that decided the outcome of the 1800 presidential election, Gallatin helped Thomas Jefferson secure victory over his ostensible running mate, Aaron Burr.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Along with Secretary of State Madison and Jefferson himself, Gallatin became one of the three key officials in the Jefferson administration.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] As Jefferson and Madison spent the majority of the summer months at their respective estates, Gallatin was frequently left to preside over the operations of the federal government.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] He also acted as a moderating force on Jefferson's speeches and policies, in one case convincing Jefferson to refrain from calling for the abolition of the General Welfare Clause.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Hofstra University professor Alan Singer argued based on this speech that Gallatin "was certainly not an abolitionist" and that "his claims to oppose slavery can also be read as racist attacks on the humanity of Africans, which was not uncommon among Whites during the antebellum era".
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] With Gallatin taking charge of fiscal policy, the new administration sought to lower taxation (though not import duties), spending, and the national debt; debt reduction in particular had long been a key goal of the party and Gallatin himself.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] When Gallatin took office in 1801, the national debt stood at $83 million.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] By 1812, the U.S. national debt had fallen to $45.2 million.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Shortly after taking office, Gallatin worked with House Ways and Means Committee Chairman John Randolph to reduce federal spending and reduce or abolish all internal taxes, including the tax on whiskey.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] He presided over dramatic reductions in military spending, particularly for the United States Navy.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Despite his opposition to debt, Gallatin strongly supported and arranged the financing for the Louisiana Purchase, in which the U.S. bought French Louisiana.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Both Jefferson and Gallatin regarded control of the port of New Orleans, which was ceded in the purchase, as the key to the development of the Western United States.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Jefferson had doubts about the constitutionality of the purchase, but Gallatin helped convince the president that a constitutional amendment authorizing the purchase was impractical and unnecessary.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin also championed and helped plan the Lewis and Clark Expedition to explore lands west of the Mississippi River.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Before and after the Louisiana Purchase, Gallatin presided over a major expansion of public land sales.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] With the goal of selling land directly to settlers rather than to land speculators, Gallatin increased the number of federal land offices from four to eighteen.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In 1812, Congress established the United States General Land Office as part of the Department of the Treasury, charging the new office with overseeing public lands.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] To help develop western lands, Gallatin advocated for internal improvements such as roads and canals, especially those that would connect to territories west of the Appalachian Mountains.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In 1805, despite his earlier constitutional reservations, Jefferson announced his support for federally financed infrastructure projects.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Three years later, Gallatin put forward his *Report on Roads and Canals*, in which he advocated for a $20 million federal infrastructure program.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Among his proposals were canals through Cape Cod, the Delmarva Peninsula, and the Great Dismal Swamp, a road stretching from Maine to Georgia, a series of canals connecting the Hudson River with the Great Lakes, and various other canals to connect seaports like Charleston with interior regions.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Resistance from many congressional Democratic-Republicans regarding cost, as well as hostilities with Britain, prevented the passage of a major infrastructure bill, but Gallatin did win funding for the construction of the National Road.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] The National Road linked the town of Cumberland, on the Potomac River, with the town of Wheeling, which sat on the Ohio River.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Many of Gallatin's other proposals were eventually carried out years later by state and local governments, as well as private citizens.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Throughout much of Jefferson's presidency, France and Britain were engaged in the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] During Jefferson's second term, the British and French both stepped up efforts to interdict American trade with their respective enemy.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] A major point of contentions in Anglo-American relations was the Royal Navy's practise of impressing alleged deserters from American merchantmen, which the U.S. public saw as an affront to America's national honor.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Jefferson sent James Monroe to Britain to negotiate a renewal and revision of the 1795 Jay Treaty, but Jefferson rejected the treaty that Monroe reached with the British.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] After the 1807 *Chesapeake*–*Leopard* affair, Jefferson proposed, over Gallatin's strong objections, what would become the Embargo Act of 1807.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] That act forbade all American ships from engaging in almost all foreign trade, and it remained in place until its repeal in the final days of Jefferson's presidency.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Despite Gallatin's objection to the embargo, he was tasked with enforcing it against smugglers, who were able to evade the embargo in various ways.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] The embargo proved ineffective at accomplishing its intended purpose of punishing Britain and France, and it contributed to growing dissent in New England against the Jefferson administration.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Overcoming Jefferson's declining popularity and the resentment at the embargo, Secretary of State Madison won the 1808 presidential election.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] After taking office, Madison sought to appoint Gallatin as Secretary of State, which was generally seen as the most prestigious cabinet position.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Opposition from the Senate convinced Madison to retain Gallatin as Secretary of the Treasury, and Robert Smith instead received the appointment as Secretary of State.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin was deeply displeased by the appointment of Smith, and he was frequently criticized by Smith's brother, Senator Samuel Smith, as well as journalist William Duane of the influential *Philadelphia Aurora*.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] He considered resigning from government service, but Madison convinced him to stay on as a key cabinet official and adviser.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In 1810, Gallatin published *Report on the Subject of Manufactures*, in which he unsuccessfully urged Congress to create a $20 million federal loan program to support fledgling manufacturers.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] He was also unable to convince Congress to renew the charter of the First Bank of the United States (commonly known as the national bank).
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Although the national bank had been established as part of Hamilton's economic program, and Jefferson believed that it was "one of the most deadly hostility existing against the principles and form of our Constitution," Gallatin saw the national bank as a key part of the country's financial system.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In a letter to Jefferson, Gallatin argued that the bank was indispensable because it served as a place of deposit for government funds, a source of credit, and a regulator of currency.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In January 1811, the national bank was effectively abolished after the House and the Senate both defeated bills to recharter the national bank in extremely narrow votes.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In response, Gallatin sent a letter to Madison, asking for permission to resign and criticizing the president for various actions, including his failure to take a strong stance on the national bank.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Shortly afterwards, Madison replaced Secretary of State Smith with James Monroe, and Gallatin withdrew his resignation request.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Following the repeal of the Embargo Act of 1807, Gallatin was charged with enforcing the Non-Intercourse Act of 1809, which lifted parts of the trade embargo but still prevented American ships from engaging in trade with the British and French.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In 1811, Congress replaced the Non-Intercourse Act of 1809 with a law known as Macon's Bill Number 2, which authorized the president to restore trade with either France or Britain if either promised to respect American neutrality.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] As with previous embargo policies pursued by the federal government under Jefferson and Madison, Macon's Bill Number 2 proved to be ineffective at halting the attacks on American shipping.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In June 1812, Madison signed a declaration of war against Britain, beginning the War of 1812.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Madison ordered an invasion of Canada by relying on mostly state militias, but British forces defeated all American invasion attempts.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] The U.S. experienced some successes at sea, but was unable to break the British blockade.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] With the abolition of the national bank, the drop in import duties due to the war, and the inability or unwillingness of state banks to furnish credit, Gallatin struggled to fund the war.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Reluctantly, he drafted and won passage of several new tax laws, as well as an increase in tariff rates.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] He also sold U.S. securities to investors, and an infusion of cash from wealthy investors Stephen Girard, John Jacob Astor, and David Parish proved critical to the financing of the war.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] During the War of 1812, the national debt grew dramatically, going from $45 million in early 1812 to $127 million in January 1816.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In 1813, President James Madison sent Gallatin to St.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Petersburg, Russia to serve as a negotiator for a peace agreement to end the War of 1812.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] He was one of five American commissioners who would negotiate the treaty, serving alongside Henry Clay, James Bayard, Jonathan Russell, and John Quincy Adams.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Efforts at starting negotiations in Russia quickly collapsed.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] While waiting abroad in the hope of future negotiations, Gallatin was replaced as Secretary of the Treasury by George W.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Campbell, with the expectation that Gallatin would take up his old post upon his return to the United States.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Negotiations with the British finally commenced in Ghent in mid-1814.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Negotiations at Ghent lasted for four months.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] The British could have chosen to shift resources to North America after the abdication of Napoleon in April 1814, but, as Gallatin learned from Alexander Baring, many in Britain were tired of war.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In December 1814, the two sides agreed to sign the Treaty of Ghent, which essentially represented a return to the *status quo ante bellum*.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] The treaty did not address the issue of impressment, but that issue became a moot point after the British and their allies defeated Napoleon for a final time at the June 1815 Battle of Waterloo.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin's patience and skill in dealing with not only the British but also his fellow members of the American commission, including Clay and Adams, made the treaty "the special and peculiar triumph of Mr.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] After the end of the war, Gallatin negotiated a commercial treaty providing for a resumption of trade between the United States and Britain.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] When Gallatin returned from Europe in September 1815, he declined Madison's request to take up his old post as Secretary of the Treasury.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] He did, however, help convince Congress to charter the Second Bank of the United States as a replacement for the defunct First Bank of the United States.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin considered going into business with his longtime friend, John Jacob Astor, but ultimately he accepted appointment as ambassador to France.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] He served in that position from 1816 to 1823.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Though he did not approve of the prevailing ideology of the Bourbon Restoration, Gallatin and his family enjoyed living in Paris.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] While serving as ambassador to France, he helped negotiate the Rush–Bagot Treaty and the Treaty of 1818, two treaties with Britain that settled several issues left over from the War of 1812 and established joint Anglo-American control over Oregon Country.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Upon returning to the United States, Gallatin agreed to serve as William H.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Crawford's running mate in the 1824 presidential election, but later withdrew from the race at Crawford's request.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Crawford had originally hoped that Gallatin's presence on the ticket would help him win the support of Pennsylvania voters, but the emergence of General Andrew Jackson as a presidential contender caused Crawford to refocus his campaign on other states.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Though Gallatin had never wanted the role, he was humiliated when he was forced to withdraw from the race.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin and his wife returned to Friendship Hill after the presidential election, living there until 1826.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] That year, Gallatin accepted appointment as ambassador to Britain.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] After negotiating an extension of the Anglo-American control of Oregon Country, Gallatin returned to the United States in November 1827.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin moved to New York City in 1828 and became president of the National Bank of New York the following year.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] He attempted to persuade President Jackson to recharter the Second Bank of the United States, but Jackson vetoed a recharter bill and the Second Bank lost its federal charter in 1836.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In 1831, Gallatin helped found New York University, and in 1843 he was elected president of the New York Historical Society.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In the mid-1840s, he opposed President James K.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Polk's expansionist policies and wrote a widely-read pamphlet, *Peace with Mexico*, that called for an end to the Mexican–American War.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin was deeply interested in Native Americans, and he favored their assimilation into European-American culture as an alternative to forced relocation.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] He drew upon government contacts to research Native Americans, gathering information through Lewis Cass, explorer William Clark, and Thomas McKenney of the Bureau of Indian Affairs.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin developed a personal relationship with Cherokee tribal leader John Ridge, who provided him with information on the vocabulary and the structure of the Cherokee language.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin's research resulted in two published works: *A Table of Indian Languages of the United States* (1826) and *Synopsis of the Indian Tribes of North America* (1836).
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] His research led him to conclude that the natives of North and South America were linguistically and culturally related and that their common ancestors had migrated from Asia in prehistoric times.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Later research efforts included examination of the language of certain native societies in Mexico and Central America.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In 1843, he co-founded the American Ethnological Society, serving as the society's first president.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] The health of both Gallatin and his wife declined in the late 1840s, and Hannah died in May 1849.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] On Sunday, August 12, Gallatin died in Astoria, now in the Borough of Queens, New York at age 88.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] He is interred at Trinity Churchyard in New York City.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin was the last surviving member of the Jefferson cabinet and the last surviving senator from the 18th century.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] In 1791, Gallatin was elected to the American Philosophical Society.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] He is commemorated in the naming of a number of counties, roads, and streets, as well as through his association with New York University.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] The Gallatin River, named by the Lewis and Clark expedition, is one of three rivers (along with the Jefferson River and the Madison River) that converge near Three Forks, Montana to form the Missouri River.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] The town of Three Forks is in Gallatin County, Montana, and Montana also hosts Gallatin National Forest and Gallatin Range.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin, Tennessee, the seat of Sumner County are also named for Gallatin as are Gallatin County, Illinois and Gallatin County, Kentucky.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin's home of Friendship Hill is maintained by the National Park Service.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] A statue of Gallatin stands at the northern entrance of the Treasury Building; a statue of Hamilton stands at the building's southern entrance.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] The Albert Gallatin Area School District, located in southwestern Fayette County, Pennsylvania, and having contained within Gallatin's home, Friendship Hill, is also named after Gallatin.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Businessman Albert Gallatin Edwards (who founded his eponymous brokerage firm in 1887 which folded into Wachovia in 2007) was named after Gallatin.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin's name is associated with NYU's Gallatin School of Individualized Study.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] New York University's internal course enrollment website for matriculating students is named "NYU Albert", after Gallatin.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin is featured on three U.S. stamps, including one issued in 1967 with the unusual denomination of 1+1⁄4¢.
[src:william-branch-giles/albert-gallatin] Gallatin is also portrayed in the center of the $500 denomination set of Greenbacks (series 1862–63) currency issue.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] Harrison is the first governor of Virginia to have been born in the 20th century.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] Harrison was born in Alberta, Virginia, the son of Albertis Sydney Harrison and Lizzie, (née Goodrich).
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] He has been widely reported as related to Benjamin Harrison V who signed the Declaration of Independence and two United States presidents, William Henry Harrison and Benjamin Harrison, the 9th and 23rd Presidents, however before his death, he found this to be false.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] He received a Bachelor of Laws degree from the University of Virginia Law School in 1928.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] Harrison married Lacey Virginia Barkley in 1930.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] They had two children: Antoinette H Jamison and Albertis S.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] Harrison III; and 6 grandchildren: Joseph D.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] Goodrich Harrison, Monica Harrison Kopf, Virginia Lacey Jamison, and James Carper Jamison II.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] Harrison went into legal practice in Lawrenceville, Virginia, where he became town attorney, before being elected commonwealth's attorney of Brunswick County.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] He was elected to the Senate of Virginia in 1947.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] He served there for ten years, before being elected Attorney General of Virginia in 1957.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] Harrison resigned as attorney general in April 1961 to run for governor, winning election that November with 63.84% of the vote, defeating Republican H.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] His administration increased educational financing for new schools and laboratories and raised teachers' pay.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] He promoted the development of state-supported colleges and technical schools as well as improved vocational training.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] He helped to modernize state banking laws to attract investment and accelerated highway construction.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] He sat on the Virginia Supreme Court of Appeals, later renamed the Supreme Court of Virginia, from 1968 to 1981.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] In 1968 he chaired the Commission on Constitutional Revision that drafted the 1971 Constitution of Virginia.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] As Attorney General, Harrison was responsible for defending the state's resistance to school integration, as part of the Massive Resistance strategy endorsed and led by the state's political leader, United States Senator Harry F.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] Part of Massive Resistance involved the closing of public schools in various Virginia cities and counties to prevent racially integrated classrooms.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] County School Board of Prince Edward County* (1952) was one of the companion cases to *Brown v.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] Board of Education* (1954), but the Supreme Court had left enforcement to the local federal district judge.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] Moreover, the Gray Commission of Byrd loyalists had recommended passage of various laws to avoid or delay integration.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] After opinions by the Virginia Supreme Court on January 19, 1959, as well as a three-judge federal panel overturned much of the new Virginia legislation, Governor J.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] Lindsay Almond (previously attorney general) and Harrison decided not to defy those courts and allowed schools in Arlington and Norfolk to reopen.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] However the schools in Prince Edward County closed in 1958 and did not reopen until 1963, as white students used tuition grants to attend a private segregation academy at state expense, while black students were left to volunteer efforts.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] Other problematic school closures, ultimately opened pursuant to federal court orders included those in Albemarle, Warren County and later New Kent County (the subject of the 1968 Supreme Court decision in *Green v.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] County School Board of New Kent County* (1968).
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] Harrison told the board to comply unless they were willing to risk prosecution.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] By this time, he, like a number of other Byrd Democrats, had concluded that obstinate resistance to integration could not continue.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] Another aspect of Massive Resistance involved new laws regulating attorney ethics, designed to attack practices of the NAACP, which was pursuing the desegregation actions.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] Supreme Court deferred to an upcoming decision of the Virginia Supreme Court about those new ethics rules in *Harrison v.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] NAACP* (1959), but the case came before it twice more in *NAACP v.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] Button* (1963) (which was reargued after Harrison resigned as attorney general to run for governor, and which Virginia lost under attorney general Robert Young Button.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] Harrison died of a heart attack at his home in Lawrenceville on January 23, 1995.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] He is buried in Oakwood Cemetery in Lawrenceville, Virginia.
[src:william-branch-giles/albertis-harrison] The courthouse in Lawrenceville is named in his honor.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] He was born and died in Amelia County, where he built his home, The Wigwam.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] Giles attended Prince Edward Academy, now Hampden–Sydney College, and the College of New Jersey, now Princeton University; he probably followed Samuel Stanhope Smith, who was teaching at Prince Edward Academy when he was appointed President of the College in 1779.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] Admitted to the Virginia bar in 1786, Giles supported the new Constitution during the ratification debates of 1788 but was not a member of the ratifying convention.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] House of Representatives in a special election in 1790, taking the seat of Theodorick Bland, who had died in office on June 1; he is believed to be the first member of the United States Congress to be elected in a special election.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] He was to be re-elected three times; he resigned on October 2, 1798, on the grounds of ill health and in disgust at the Alien and Sedition Acts.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] During this first period in Congress, he fervently supported his fellow Virginians James Madison and Thomas Jefferson against Alexander Hamilton and his ideas for a national bank preferring Jefferson's idea of an agrarian republic.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] Per this goal, he opposed the pro-British Jay's Treaty and resisted naval appropriation to be used against France during the Quasi-War.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] In the same year, he voted for the Kentucky and Virginia Resolutions in the House of Delegates to declare the Alien and Sedition Acts unconstitutional.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] After another term in the House, from 1801 to 1803, Giles was appointed as a Senator from Virginia after the resignation of Wilson Cary Nicholas in 1804.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] Giles served in the US Senate and was reappointed in 1810 until he resigned on March 3, 1815.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] Giles strongly advocated the removal of Justice Samuel Chase after his impeachment, urging the Senate to consider it as a political decision (as to whether the people of the United States should have confidence in Chase) rather than as a trial.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] Giles was deeply disappointed by the acquittal of Chase.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] He supported the election of Madison as president in 1808, in preference to the Federalist candidate Charles Cotesworth Pinckney.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] Giles was Madison's chief advocate in Virginia.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] After the election, however, he joined with Senator Samuel Smith of Maryland and his brother Robert Smith, the Secretary of State, in criticizing Madison; first as too weak on Britain and then, in 1812, as too precipitate in going to war; however, voted for the declaration of war.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] He disliked Albert Gallatin, the Secretary of the Treasury, who was primarily responsible for preventing his nomination as Secretary of State and defeating Gallatin's bill of 1811 for a new Bank of the United States.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] Giles's refusal to accept the General Assembly's instructions led to his rejection at the next poll for a senator.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] (The state legislatures elected senators in those days.) Giles served one relatively uneventful term in the Virginia House of Delegates in 1816–1817 and then retired from political office for a time.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] He attacked John Quincy Adams and Henry Clay as he had attacked Hamilton, calling them corrupt Anglophiles.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] Giles also published a criticism of the Jeffersonian program for public education.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] Giles argued that it was unjust to tax one man to educate another man's children, and the teachers that the government employed would constitute a special interest, always ready to vote for higher taxes and government spending.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] Besides, he said, giving every boy in Virginia three years of school would have limited practical utility, deprive farm families of much-needed labor power, and leave the typical "scholar" unfitted for the return to hard labor that awaited him.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] When James Barbour left the Senate in 1825, Giles attempted to persuade the legislature to appoint him as a replacement; they appointed John Randolph instead.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] In 1826, Giles was again elected to the House of Delegates, and in 1827 he was elected Governor; Giles served as Governor of Virginia for three terms, from March 4, 1827, to March 4, 1830.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] From the governorship, Giles encouraged Virginia's Senator Littleton Waller Tazewell to organize a southern resistance to the American System of Henry Clay centered on a boycott on northern manufactures.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] Tazewell found little support for it among southern senators.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] In Giles's last term, he was a member of the Virginia Constitutional Convention of 1829–1830 where he strongly supported the existing apportionment of the House of Delegates, giving the eastern counties of Virginia, with a minority of the voters, control of the legislature.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] He did favor reform of the suffrage requirements, however.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] Giles also opposed the movement in the convention to strengthen his own office, the governorship.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] Strong governorships in other states, such as New York, were at the center of political machines kept together by patronage and corruption, he said, and the reason that Virginia had not suffered from those ills was that the governorship in his state was too weak to be worth fighting for.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] Rather than follow the example of New York, with its party machine, it was better for Virginia to retain George Mason's executive model.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] Giles lost to some extent: while the governor's term remained short and was still accountable to the General Assembly, the Constitution of 1830 abolished the privy council, thus making the governorship a bit more independent.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] Giles married twice; first in 1797, to Martha Peyton Tabb, the widow of patriot John Tabb.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] Giles built his 18-room house, "The Wigwam," for her.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] After she died in 1808, he married Frances Ann Gwynn in 1810 and had three more children.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] Giles's historical reputation has been mixed.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] Claude Bowers called Oliver's appraisal a "wretchedly unfair caricature" and advanced a favorable view, noting, among other things, praise that Giles received from Patrick Henry, John Randolph of Roanoke, and other contemporaries.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] Counties in two states were named in his honor: Giles County, Virginia and Giles County, Tennessee.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] His name also graces a residence hall at the College of William and Mary.
[src:william-branch-giles/william-branch-giles] The Wigwam was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1969.
